#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:209
msgid "Testing plugins"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:211
msgid ""
"pytest comes with some facilities that you can enable for testing your "
"plugin.  Given that you have an installed plugin you can enable the :py:"
"class:`testdir <_pytest.pytester.Testdir>` fixture via specifying a command "
"line option to include the pytester plugin (``-p pytester``) or by putting "
"``pytest_plugins = \"pytester\"`` into your test or ``conftest.py`` file.  "
"You then will have a ``testdir`` fixture which you can use like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:219
msgid ""
"# content of test_myplugin.py\n"
"\n"
"pytest_plugins = \"pytester\"  # to get testdir fixture\n"
"\n"
"def test_myplugin(testdir):\n"
"    testdir.makepyfile(\"\"\"\n"
"        def test_example():\n"
"            pass\n"
"    \"\"\")\n"
"    result = testdir.runpytest(\"--verbose\")\n"
"    result.fnmatch_lines(\"\"\"\n"
"        test_example*\n"
"    \"\"\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:233
msgid ""
"Note that by default ``testdir.runpytest()`` will perform a pytest in-"
"process.  You can pass the command line option ``--runpytest=subprocess`` to "
"have it happen in a subprocess."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:237
msgid ""
"Also see the :py:class:`RunResult <_pytest.pytester.RunResult>` for more "
"methods of the result object that you get from a call to ``runpytest``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:243
msgid "Writing hook functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:249
msgid "hook function validation and execution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:251
msgid ""
"pytest calls hook functions from registered plugins for any given hook "
"specification.  Let's look at a typical hook function for the "
"``pytest_collection_modifyitems(session, config, items)`` hook which pytest "
"calls after collection of all test items is completed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:257
msgid ""
"When we implement a ``pytest_collection_modifyitems`` function in our plugin "
"pytest will during registration verify that you use argument names which "
"match the specification and bail out if not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:261
msgid "Let's look at a possible implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:263
msgid ""
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(config, items):\n"
"    # called after collection is completed\n"
"    # you can modify the ``items`` list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:269
msgid ""
"Here, ``pytest`` will pass in ``config`` (the pytest config object) and "
"``items`` (the list of collected test items) but will not pass in the "
"``session`` argument because we didn't list it in the function signature.  "
"This dynamic \"pruning\" of arguments allows ``pytest`` to be \"future-"
"compatible\": we can introduce new hook named parameters without breaking "
"the signatures of existing hook implementations.  It is one of the reasons "
"for the general long-lived compatibility of pytest plugins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:277
msgid ""
"Note that hook functions other than ``pytest_runtest_*`` are not allowed to "
"raise exceptions.  Doing so will break the pytest run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:283
msgid "firstresult: stop at first non-None result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:285
msgid ""
"Most calls to ``pytest`` hooks result in a **list of results** which "
"contains all non-None results of the called hook functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:288
msgid ""
"Some hook specifications use the ``firstresult=True`` option so that the "
"hook call only executes until the first of N registered functions returns a "
"non-None result which is then taken as result of the overall hook call. The "
"remaining hook functions will not be called in this case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:295
msgid "hookwrapper: executing around other hooks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:301
msgid ""
"pytest plugins can implement hook wrappers which wrap the execution of other "
"hook implementations.  A hook wrapper is a generator function which yields "
"exactly once. When pytest invokes hooks it first executes hook wrappers and "
"passes the same arguments as to the regular hooks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:306
msgid ""
"At the yield point of the hook wrapper pytest will execute the next hook "
"implementations and return their result to the yield point in the form of a :"
"py:class:`CallOutcome` instance which encapsulates a result or exception "
"info.  The yield point itself will thus typically not raise exceptions "
"(unless there are bugs)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:312
msgid "Here is an example definition of a hook wrapper::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:314
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.hookimpl(hookwrapper=True)\n"
"def pytest_pyfunc_call(pyfuncitem):\n"
"    # do whatever you want before the next hook executes\n"
"\n"
"    outcome = yield\n"
"    # outcome.excinfo may be None or a (cls, val, tb) tuple\n"
"\n"
"    res = outcome.get_result()  # will raise if outcome was exception\n"
"    # postprocess result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:326
msgid ""
"Note that hook wrappers don't return results themselves, they merely perform "
"tracing or other side effects around the actual hook implementations. If the "
"result of the underlying hook is a mutable object, they may modify that "
"result but it's probably better to avoid it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:333
msgid "Hook function ordering / call example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:335
msgid ""
"For any given hook specification there may be more than one implementation "
"and we thus generally view ``hook`` execution as a ``1:N`` function call "
"where ``N`` is the number of registered functions. There are ways to "
"influence if a hook implementation comes before or after others, i.e.  the "
"position in the ``N``-sized list of functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:341
msgid ""
"# Plugin 1\n"
"@pytest.hookimpl(tryfirst=True)\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(items):\n"
"    # will execute as early as possible\n"
"\n"
"# Plugin 2\n"
"@pytest.hookimpl(trylast=True)\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(items):\n"
"    # will execute as late as possible\n"
"\n"
"# Plugin 3\n"
"@pytest.hookimpl(hookwrapper=True)\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(items):\n"
"    # will execute even before the tryfirst one above!\n"
"    outcome = yield\n"
"    # will execute after all non-hookwrappers executed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:360
msgid "Here is the order of execution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:362
msgid ""
"Plugin3's pytest_collection_modifyitems called until the yield point because "
"it is a hook wrapper."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:365
msgid ""
"Plugin1's pytest_collection_modifyitems is called because it is marked with "
"``tryfirst=True``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:368
msgid ""
"Plugin2's pytest_collection_modifyitems is called because it is marked with "
"``trylast=True`` (but even without this mark it would come after Plugin1)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:372
msgid ""
"Plugin3's pytest_collection_modifyitems then executing the code after the "
"yield point.  The yield receives a :py:class:`CallOutcome` instance which "
"encapsulates the result from calling the non-wrappers.  Wrappers shall not "
"modify the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/writing_plugins.rst:376
msgid ""
"It's possible to use ``tryfirst`` and ``trylast`` also in conjunction with "
"``hookwrapper=True`` in which case it will influence the ordering of "
"hookwrappers among each other."
msgstr ""

